<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-11-30T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-11-30T21:00:00-05:00" n="812" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d812">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11385: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-01T10:00:00+08:00">December 1, 1937—10
                                        a.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 1—7 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>9. German Ambassador<note n="63" xml:id="d812fn63">Oskar
                                    Trautmann.</note> left Hankow this morning accompanied by the
                                Counsellor of Embassy for Kiukiang and Kuling on customs cruiser
                                loaned by the Chinese Government. No information can be obtained
                                regarding his mission but the natural inference is that he bears to
                                General Chiang some sort of peace proposal from the Japanese.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Nanking, Peiping, Shanghai. Peiping repeat to Tokyo.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>